1 Initializing a temporary GRASS project

gisbase_grass <- ifelse(.Platform$OS.type == "windows", 
                        link2GI::paramGRASSw()$gisbase_GRASS[1],
                        link2GI::paramGRASSx()$gisbase_GRASS[1])
initGRASS(gisBase = gisbase_grass,
          home = tempdir(), 
          mapset = "PERMANENT")

2 GRASS workflow

2.1 Loading data from WFS

In case GRASS will work directly on pre-existing data in the cloud or on disk, it’s more efficient to let GRASS load those directly than to read them in R and then use rgrass7::writeXXX(). The latter will first write a temporary GPKG or GeoTIFF file from R, after which GRASS is instructed to read that file. So that route is most convenient for intermediate data created in R.

execshell("v.in.ogr input='https://geoservices.informatievlaanderen.be/overdrachtdiensten/BWK/wfs?service=WFS&request=GetFeature&typename=BWK%3ABwkhab&bbox=130000%2C184000%2C138000%2C194000' output=habbox -o")
# execGRASS() currently has bug because of '&' in URL:
# url <- "https://geoservices.informatievlaanderen.be/overdrachtdiensten/BWK/wfs?service=WFS&request=GetFeature&typename=BWK%3ABwkhab&bbox=130000%2C184000%2C138000%2C194000"
# execGRASS("v.in.ogr",
#           "o",
#           input = url,
#           output = "habbox")

2.3 Rasterizing result

# note that stringexecGRASS() cannot split '-sa' as 
# '-s -a', which is needed for execGRASS()
execshell("g.region vector=habeval res=1 -sa
           g.region -p
           v.to.rast input=habeval output=reval use=cat label_column=EVAL memory=2048")
